{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"crust-fetch-stump","description":"## Context\n(Placeholder epic — scoping TBD.) rebar currently records NO session identifier on a claim that is distinct from `assignee` and the event `author`. A claim writes a `STATUS` event + (when an assignee is given) an `EDIT` event; the envelope carries `timestamp`, per-event `uuid`, `event_type`, `author` (git user), and `env_id` — but `env_id` is the **tracker init-environment id** (written once at `rebar init`, shared by ALL events), not a per-session/per-agent id. The `session_log` ticket type is tracked by a local git-ignored pointer (`.rebar/current_session_log`) and is **not** linked to claims. So today there is no claim->session linkage in the event schema (see investigation in session logs / bug context).\n\n## What\nWhen a session/agent identifier is present in the environment (e.g. an agent runner exports something like `CLAUDE_SESSION_ID`, or a rebar-specific `REBAR_SESSION_ID`), automatically record it on the claim so a tickets in_progress state is attributable to the specific session that claimed it — additively, without disturbing `assignee`/`author`.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A claim performed while a recognized session env var is set durably records that session id, queryable later, distinct from assignee/author.\n- Absent the env var, behavior is unchanged (no session id recorded; fully backward compatible).\n- The recorded session id survives compaction and is preserved-and-ignored by older clones (event-schema rollout convention).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Decide the env-var contract (which var name(s) are recognized; precedence if multiple).\n- [ ] Decide the storage shape (new event field vs a dedicated event type vs reducer state key) and whether it syncs to Jira (likely local-only, like session_log).\n- [ ] Claim records the session id when the env var is present; no-op when absent.\n- [ ] Read surface to retrieve the claiming session id for a ticket.\n- [ ] Backward/forward compatible (compaction-safe; older clones tolerate it).\n- [ ] Break the epic into child stories/tasks before implementation (this is a placeholder).","id":"38ec-5f12-fdf5-4340","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"epic","title":"Track a claim<->session relationship, auto-recorded from environment variables when present"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782756165513355001,"uuid":"dcf9021b-2dd8-4e7f-9c9c-dbeeaad317e5"}